.\"	$OpenBSD: lam.1,v 1.2 1996/06/26 05:34:49 deraadt Exp $
.\"	$NetBSD: lam.1,v 1.2 1994/11/14 20:27:40 jtc Exp $
d37 15
a51 15
.TH LAM 1 "June 6, 1993"
.UC 4
.SH NAME
lam \- laminate files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lam [ \-[fp]
min.max
.B ] [ \-s
sepstring
.B ] [ \-t
c
.B ]
file ...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Lam
d54 1
a54 1
.IR n -th
d56 1
a56 1
.IR file s
d58 1
a58 1
.IR n -th
d60 4
a63 2
The name `\fB\-\fP' means the standard input, and may be repeated.
.PP
d65 1
a65 1
.I file
d70 2
a71 1
.IP \fB\-f\fP\ min.max
d73 1
a73 1
.IR min.max ,
d75 1
a75 1
.I min
d77 1
a77 1
.I max
d80 1
a80 1
.I min
d82 3
a84 1
and if it begins with a `\-', the fragment will be left-adjusted
d86 3
a88 2
.IP \fB\-p\fP\ min.max
Like \fB\-f\fP,
d91 1
a91 1
.IP \fB\-s\fP\ sepstring
d93 1
a93 1
.I sepstring
d96 1
a96 1
.IP \fB\-t\fP\ c
d98 1
a98 1
.I c
d101 2
a102 1
.PP
d104 2
a105 13
.IR pr (1).
.SH EXAMPLES
.de IC
.IP
.ss 36
.ft B
..
.de NC
.br
.ss 12
.PP
..
.PP
d107 2
a108 3
.IC
$ lam file1 file2 file3 file4
.NC
d111 1
a111 1
.IC
a112 1
.br
d114 2
a115 1
.NC
d117 10
a126 9
.IC
$ lam \- \- < file
.NC
and a form letter with substitutions keyed by `@@' can be done with
.IC
$ lam \-t @@ letter changes
.NC
.SH SEE ALSO
join(1), pr(1), printf(3)
